    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Atriplex albicans, Exomis albicans</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_9621",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Smallish shrub with branches spreading along the ground and then curving upwards. Young branches with raised longitudinal ridges but become woody when older. Leaves arranges alternately along branches, spear-shaped with a short stalk and prominent mid-vein.</p><p>Inconspicuous pale-yellow flowers occur in clusters at the end of the stems. Striking brown to orange fruitlets appear lower down the stems and are enclosed in fleshy bracts. They have a strong melon-like small when crushed.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9622",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Plants up to about 1 m tall. Leaves about 25 mm long.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9623",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to Southern Africa. Introduced to St Helena.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Southern Namibia to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9624",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Widely distributed in arid regions both along the coast and further inland and can survive in saline soils right along the coast. Heavily browed by grazing herbivores and its presence is an indication of good land management. Thought to have potential for the rehabilitation of saline soils.</p><p>Also used by indigenous people to wash hands or clothes, hence the common name soap bush.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9625",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9626",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers September to January. Easily propagated from seeds by collecting and planting the bracts enclosing the fruit and tiny seeds and is useful in coastal gardens.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9627",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The only species in the genus and fairly easily recognised by the unusual succulent bracts around the fruit.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9628",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
